Let=E2=80=99s say you run a pension fund for employees of some company or s=
tate government, and an asset manager comes to you with a proposition:
=09She runs a fund that gets better returns, with lower risk=C2=A0and lower=
 fees, than any other available investment opportunity.=09She will let you =
put your pension=E2=80=99s money into her fund.=09The cost of this outperfo=
rmance, though, is that she will=C2=A0murder one of your beneficiaries ever=
y week.

Is this a good trade? Should you say yes?=C2=A0On the one hand, you are a=
=C2=A0pension fund manager, and your job is to maximize the returns on your=
 pension fund and the=C2=A0retirement benefits of your beneficiaries. If yo=
u put your money in her fund, you will get good performance, and you will b=
e able to write pleasing annual reports about how much the fund went up. In=
 terms of doing your core job, you would be doing it well. On the other han=
d, I think if you asked your beneficiaries =E2=80=94=C2=A0the people to who=
m you have fiduciary duties =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwould you accept a bett=
er-performing and more stable pension fund that can pay higher retirement b=
enefits, in exchange for a good chance of being murdered by the fund manage=
r?=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0probably a lot of them would say no? Because of =
the murder?
This is not a real product. But there are two main ways for an asset manage=
r (or pension fund manager) to think about environmental, social and govern=
ance investing:
=09Considering ESG factors will allow fund managers to get higher and more =
sustainable financial returns, because companies that are bad at ESG face h=
igher long-term risks;=C2=A0or
=09Never mind financial returns: Our beneficiaries live on a planet, and if=
 companies destroy it then they won=E2=80=99t be able to live there anymore=
, so we should not give companies our beneficiaries=E2=80=99 money to spend=
 on destroying the planet.

These views are not=C2=A0exactly=C2=A0mutually exclusive, but there is   so=
me intellectual tension between them. Still ESG-focused investment managers=
 do have a tendency to emphasize both: They mostly=C2=A0say=C2=A0that they =
are looking to maximize risk-adjusted financial returns, but they also at l=
east implicitly appeal to people who care about environmental and social is=
sues
  [4]
=C2=A0for their own sake.
There are two=C2=A0exactly identical=C2=A0ways to think about the trend of=
=C2=A0anti-ESG=C2=A0investing, where Republicans in the US try to prevent a=
sset managers from considering ESG factors:
=09Asset managers who consider ESG factors are prioritizing their environme=
ntal and social goals over financial returns; they are sacrificing benefici=
aries=E2=80=99 retirement savings for the manager=E2=80=99s=C2=A0personal a=
nd political preferences.=09Asset managers who do ESG=C2=A0are=C2=A0making =
society worse:=C2=A0They are pulling money from oil companies and gun compa=
nies or whatever, and if you are an anti-ESG advocate you think that oil an=
d guns are good.

Again there is something a bit contradictory here: Are you allowed to consi=
der social goals (but in a Republican way), or not? And again anti-ESG-focu=
sed managers tend to elide that tension and emphasize both: They say that t=
hey want to consider only financial returns, but they also suggest that ESG=
=E2=80=99s goals are bad in themselves.
Here is  a strange letter from John Schroder, the Louisiana state treasurer=
, to BlackRock Inc., pulling some Louisiana state funds from BlackRock beca=
use it is too ESG. Schroder manages to get both theories into two successiv=
e paragraphs:

This divestment is necessary to protect Louisiana from actions and policies=
 that would actively seek to hamstring our fossil fuel sector. In my opinio=
n, your support of ESG investing is inconsistent with the best economic int=
erests and values of Louisiana. I cannot support an institution that would =
deny our state the benefit of one of its most robust assets. Simply put, we=
 cannot be party to the crippling of our own economy.
In addition, according to my legal counsel, Environmental, Social and Gover=
nance (ESG) investing is contrary to Louisiana law on fiduciary duties, whi=
ch requires a sole focus on financial returns for the beneficiaries of stat=
e funds. Focusing on ESG=E2=80=99s political and social goals=C2=A0or placi=
ng those goals above the duty to enhance investors=E2=80=99 returns is unac=
ceptable under Louisiana law.

Look, if that second paragraph is true =E2=80=94=C2=A0if Louisiana fiduciar=
y law requires state funds to be invested with =E2=80=9Ca sole focus on fin=
ancial returns for the beneficiaries=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0then the first=
 paragraph is illegal! He=E2=80=99s saying =E2=80=9Cnever mind your financi=
al analysis, we need you to put money into our local oil companies.=E2=80=
=9D What if those oil companies have bad returns? (Or what if BlackRock=E2=
=80=99s professional investment managers think they will?) Doesn=E2=80=99t =
matter, the goal is to pump money into the local economy. But also you can =
only focus on returns.
As my Bloomberg Opinion colleague   John Authers writes=C2=A0about this let=
ter:

But the bottom line, I fear, is that it cedes an essential point to the bac=
kers of ESG. Fund managers are allowed to take the broader interests of the=
ir members into account, and not just the narrowly financial ones; and it i=
s perfectly justifiable to base investment decisions on political ends or p=
rinciples. =E2=80=A6
Louisiana is against ESG, and many of BlackRock=E2=80=99s funds are in favo=
r of it, but both are putting their political opinions about ESG over an at=
tempt to maximize investors=E2=80=99 returns.

I would quibble with that last sentence:=C2=A0BlackRock=C2=A0will certainly=
 tell you that its stance on ESG is=C2=A0not=C2=A0political, but=C2=A0purel=
y=C2=A0about maximizing risk-adjusted returns. You could disagree; certainl=
y anti-ESG advocates disagree, and I think it=E2=80=99d be hard to=C2=A0pro=
ve=C2=A0that BlackRock=E2=80=99s ESG concerns are purely financial. But the=
 intellectual framework exists for them to=C2=A0say=C2=A0it. Anti-ESG is st=
ill too new to have a convincing story for why pursuing Republican politica=
l priorities is a way to maximize returns.
Elsewhere, here is a story about how a lot of the anti-ESG push  comes from=
 Leonard Leo, the impresario of the Federalist Society.=C2=A0He is not sole=
ly concerned with=C2=A0financial returns.

