cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> venture capital investing</a> in=
 recent years =E2=80=94 though possibly not anymore? =E2=80=94=C2=A0is that=
 capital is plentiful, investment decisions are easy, and the hard part of =
the job is=C2=A0<em>deal flow</em>. Every year there are some good startups=
 raising money,=C2=A0they get to choose their investors, investors compete =
to be on the list,=C2=A0and your job, as a VC, is to win that competition a=
nd get the good deals. If your skill as a venture capitalist is raising mon=
ey from limited partners, or=C2=A0evaluating companies and deciding which o=
nes will succeed and which will fail, that=E2=80=99s no good. Everyone can =
do that; it=E2=80=99s easy to raise money and to identify the good startups=
. What=E2=80=99s hard is to get an allocation in an investment round with a=
 good startup.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If this is your model, the simplest approach m=
ight be to buy a bunch of billboards in San Francisco that say=C2=A0=E2=80=
=9Chi, we are venture investors, we have tons of money, and if you have a s=
tartup and ask us for money (1) we will give it to you (2) without asking t=
oo many questions (3) at a very high valuation.=E2=80=9D You can just publi=
cly offer founders the economic terms =E2=80=94 lots of money, limited dilu=
tion,=C2=A0certainty, ease of use, minimal distraction =E2=80=94=C2=A0that =
they want. This should make you a more attractive investor than someone who=
 wants to do a lot of due diligence and negotiates for a lower valuation an=
d a lot of governance rights.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This was, famously, more or less=C2=A0<a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDQtMTUvY29pbmJhc2Ut=
ZGlyZWN0LWxpc3RpbmctbmVlZGVkLXRoZS1jb2luLXRpY2tlcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDEzMjJfTU9=
ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT=
0yMjEwMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdce754f3=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">the approach</a> that <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDYtMDcvcmV0YWlsLXRyYWRpbmctaXMtYWJvdXQtdG8tY2hhbmdlP2Nt=
cGlkPUJCRDEwMTMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXd=
zbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4=
b8524a319a23cBce7c4989" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" targ=
et=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Tiger Global used</a>=C2=A0in recent years=
, with let=E2=80=99s say mixed success, but they certainly got a ton of dea=
l flow. It seems to have been <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM6Ly9yYW5kbGUuc3Vic3RhY2suY29tL3AvcGxheWl=
uZy1kaWZmZXJlbnQtZ2FtZXM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1f7537bd" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">viewed =
as sort of disruptive and low-status</a> by the rest of the venture capital=
 community, and so perhaps by some founders; there was possibly some negati=
ve signaling value to raising money from Tiger without any due diligence. (=
Did it mean that you=C2=A0<em>couldn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>raise money from p=
eople who did due diligence, because your company was bad? Or just that you=
 were busy and rational, and Tiger=E2=80=99s money was cheap and easy?)=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other, higher-status model is basically th=
at you appeal to founders by saying =E2=80=9Cif you take our money, you wil=
l have us on your team, and we are good to have on your team.=E2=80=9D Ther=
e are various ways to do this, various skills or benefits you can offer =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0capital-markets expertise, introductions to customers, etc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but the basic thing that you=E2=80=99re offering is yourself, y=
our advice and wisdom and presence and, if applicable, fame. (=E2=80=9CWhat=
 the top VC firms are selling today isn=E2=80=99t money=E2=80=94they=E2=80=
=99re lending their own brand to startups,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link=
.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM6Ly9rd29rY2hhaW4uY=
29tLzIwMjEvMDkvMjkvbmFycmF0aXZlLWRpc3RpbGxhdGlvbi0xLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBbf03b9bc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">writes Kevin Kwok</a>.) You, the partner at the ventu=
re capital firm, are going to take a seat on a startup=E2=80=99s board of d=
irectors, and the founder will have to go to meetings with the board, and s=
he will want those meetings to be =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cfun=E2=80=9D is m=
aybe not quite the word, but something like fun. She will want board member=
s who are smart and analytical, or wise and philosophical, or who have been=
 in her shoes and succeeded wildly, or who have been in her shoes and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMjIvbWVtZS1zdG=
9jay12YWNhdGlvbi1pcy1vdmVyP2NtcGlkPUJCRDEwMTMyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpd=
W09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMTAxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFp=
Z249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa913e17c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> failed wildl=
y in educational ways</a>, or who are celebrities with star power, or who j=
ust say cool stuff in meetings. She will want to walk out of board meetings=
 feeling energized; she will want the board meetings to make her=C2=A0<em>f=
eel=C2=A0</em>like she runs a thrilling world-changing=C2=A0company. Having=
 venture capitalists who are dynamic brilliant celebrities helps with that.=
 And so if you are a venture capitalist it is good to be a dynamic brillian=
t celebrity, because that will get you deal flow.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And by =E2=80=9Cbe a dynamic brilliant celebri=
ty=E2=80=9D I mean, of course, =E2=80=9Cwrite good tweets on Twitter,=E2=80=
=9D since that is where venture capitalists go to make jokes and impart wis=
dom, and where startup founders go to find venture capitalists. Here=E2=80=
=99s an incredible <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS90d2l0dGVyLWdob3=
N0d3JpdGVyLXNpbGljb24tdmFsbGV5LXZjLXZlbnR1cmUtZm91bmRlci1zYW4tZnJhbmNpc2NvL=
TIwMjItMTA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB862ed4f2" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">as-told-to essay at I=
nsider</a> by =E2=80=9Cthe founder of a tech startup who ghostwrites tweets=
 for venture capitalists,=E2=80=9D with a complete theory of venture capita=
l thought leadership:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The competition means the deal flow is faster =
and more cutthroat. Today, the best deals are closing within 24 hours after=
 they go on market. And there's no way to get in early, as you could in the=
 old days, because founders won't take a meeting with you before the fundin=
g round is closed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now what does that have to do with Twitter? It=
 matters because funders have to build parasocial relationships with founde=
rs. A founder might read a tweet from a VC and say: "Wow, he's a cool guy. =
He's in on the joke. I want him on my board." Establishing yourself as a fu=
nder is no longer a one-to-one format where you're building meaningful rela=
tionships. It's a one-to-many format. You're broadcasting. I'm writing the =
content that will get the attention of young founders, to establish the cre=
dibility of my clients, the VCs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Deals used to start with a meeting at the Paci=
fic-Union Club. I don't know anyone who goes there now. It all happens on T=
witter. Twitter is the new social club.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose one way to do this is to tweet wise =
thoughts about product and strategy, but that is not the <em>only</em> way =
to do it. The goal is to signal to founders =E2=80=9Cyou would like to have=
 me=C2=A0in your board meetings=E2=80=9D; strategic wisdom is helpful but s=
o are jokes, or I guess even being annoying in a way that some founders lik=
e?</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I pride myself on not sticking my foot in my m=
outh. Nothing has turned into a gaffe. There is a set of topics that no mat=
ter what you say about them, it leads to people being angry in your replies=
. And VCs will often choose to engage in those third-rail topics. For examp=
le, how many hours should you work? That's a classic. If a VC feels they're=
 not getting enough attention, they can just tweet, "You have to work 80 ho=
urs a week to be successful." Everyone will come out to tell you that you'r=
e canceled. It taps into money, privilege, class, ability to sacrifice. Peo=
ple have a lot of emotions about those subjects.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So taking risks can lead to greater attentiona=
l rewards, but the precise level of risk I'll take depends on the client. S=
ome clients don't care. They're shock jocks. They'll tweet anything. Others=
 are more careful. It's a question of what brand they're trying to build.=
=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Do you want to have board meetings where one b=
oard member is constantly saying =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTEtMjcvc29vbi1kaXJlY3QtbGlzdGluZ3Mtd2lsbC1yYW=
