<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, there are other VC skills. For inst=
ance, sometimes a startup founder will come to you with a problem. The prob=
lem is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The startup raised money last year at =
a $5 billion valuation.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Now it nee=
ds to raise more money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But it is =
only worth $3 billion, because the market is down. <a class=3D"footnote-ind=
ex" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displ=
ay: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Due to the rules of the venture c=
apital game, it is=C2=A0<em>not allowed to raise money at a lower valuation=
:=C2=A0</em>This is a =E2=80=9Cdown round,=E2=80=9D which is horribly embar=
rassing and imperils its ability to raise money, attract employees, retain =
customers, go public, etc.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" =
style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wi=
dth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importan=
t; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So it would like to raise money n=
ow, with its $3 billion value, but be able to say it is doing it at a $5 bi=
llion valuation.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Can you help?</li=
>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a problem of=C2=A0<em>financial engine=
ering</em>, and you work in finance, and surely you can help.<a class=3D"fo=
otnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !import=
ant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> One simple solution is =E2=80=9Cjust raise=C2=A0<em>debt</em>,=E2=80=
=9D and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29363474.2=
76514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9zdGFydHVwcy1maWxsLWZ1bmRpbmctZ=
2Fwcy13aXRoLWRlYnQtZGVzcGl0ZS1yaXNpbmctaW50ZXJlc3QtcmF0ZXMtMTE2NjUzOTYwMDI/=
607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6e99debd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"item=
scope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !im=
portant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bot=
tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> that is in fact a popular appro=
ach these days</a>: If you borrow money, instead of raising equity, you are=
 not picking any particular valuation and so you can avoid the question. Bu=
t there are more complicated solutions that have the advantages of (1) avoi=
ding the cash costs of debt service and=C2=A0(2) raising=C2=A0<em>venture c=
apital=C2=A0</em>rather than debt (so you, as a VC, can invest). <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cudGhlaW5mb3JtYXRpb24uY29tL2FydGljbGVzL3N0YXJ0dXBzLWF2b2lkLXZhbHVhdGlvbi1=
jdXRzLXdpdGgtdXAtcm91bmRzLWluLW5hbWUtb25seT91dG1fc291cmNlPXN1YnN0YWNrJnV0bV=
9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmcmM9MWJkaTVo/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc69ba94d" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 Mainly liquidation preferences</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fundraisings on terms that guarantee investors=
 multiples of their money back in worst-case scenarios, such as a liquidati=
on, were rare during the 2020-2021 fundraising boom when venture firms, pow=
ered by record inflows of capital, competed fiercely to back hot startups a=
nd pushed valuations ever higher. =E2=80=A6 Investors settled for terms tha=
t guaranteed they would be paid back their original investment before found=
ers and employees=E2=80=94a 1 times liquidation preference.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the pendulum has swung back as spiking int=
erest rates and the end of the stock market=E2=80=99s bull run have made in=
vestors more leery. Funding for startups fell 52% to $81 billion in the thi=
rd quarter, compared to the same period last year, according to Crunchbase.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now investors are getting better terms. [Louis=
] Lehot, the startup lawyer, said two-thirds of middle- and late-stage star=
tup deals he=E2=80=99s worked on this year have had a 2 to 3 times liquidat=
ion preference, meaning those investors would be paid back double or triple=
 their money before other stakeholders. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors like liquidation preferences so much=
 that they=E2=80=99re willing to agree to funding on valuations equal to or=
 higher than a company=E2=80=99s previous round=E2=80=94despite difficultie=
s in the startup=E2=80=99s underlying business. But they also come at a pot=
entially steep cost for founders and employees, who could get left with not=
hing.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you invest $100 million in a company at a $=
1 billion (post-money) valuation with a 2x liquidation preference, and it s=
ucceeds and goes public in three years at a $5 billion valuation, then you =
will get back $500 million, i.e. 10% of its value. If it sells itself in th=
ree years at a $500 million valuation, though, you will get back $200 milli=
on, i.e. twice your money, which is 40% of its value. In a sense, it turns =
out that you invested=C2=A0at a $250 million valuation: You put up $100 mil=
lion and ended up with 40% of the company. You invested at a valuation to b=
e determined later, but a valuation=C2=A0<em>cap=C2=A0</em>of $1 billion. B=
ut the valuation cap is what gets reported.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Back in 2017 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ3NiLnN0YW5mb3JkLmV=
kdS9mYWN1bHR5LXJlc2VhcmNoL3B1YmxpY2F0aW9ucy9zcXVhcmluZy12ZW50dXJlLWNhcGl0YW=
wtdmFsdWF0aW9ucy1yZWFsaXR5/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb2ff949f" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a pa=
per</a> called =E2=80=9CSquaring Venture Capital Valuations with Reality=E2=
=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29363474.27=
6514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDgtMD=
MvYml0Y29pbi1mb3Jrcy1hbmQtdW5pY29ybi1mYWtlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMDEzMjJfTU9ORVlTV=
FVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjEw=
MTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB05aefba4" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">  got a lot of attention</a>. The authors,=C2=A0Will Gornall and Ilya S=
trebulaev,=C2=A0argued that the headline valuations of a lot of big tech un=
icorns were overstated, because investors got various goodies (mainly liqui=
dation preferences) that reduced their effective valuations. This turned ou=
t not to be very important in the following few years, because there was a =
pretty strong tech bull market, which meant that (1) startups were increasi=
ngly able to refuse to give investors those goodies and (2) the realized va=
lue of those liquidation preferences was low. (If every $1 billion startup =
ends up=C2=A0going=C2=A0public at $5 billion, your 2x liquidation preferenc=
e doesn=E2=80=99t matter.) But now the market has turned, and VC financial =
engineering has value again.<em> </em></p>
