<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/29363474.276514/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3N0YXRl=
bWVudC9wZWlyY2Utc3RhdGVtZW50LXN1cy15ZWV0LTEwMDcyMg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
B339a2c19" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> a speech</a> that US Securities and Exchange Commission=
 Commissioner Hester Peirce gave last week about the Sarbanes-Oxley Act. Ba=
sically she thinks that some Sarbanes-Oxley provisions should be dialed bac=
k, but never mind that, here=E2=80=99s this:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The task facing legislators is som=
ewhat akin to that facing people charged with keeping dictionaries up-to-da=
te. Whether you are responsible for writing laws or dictionaries, you try t=
o be responsive to current events while maintaining a longer-term view. How=
 do you figure out which words are just fads and which merit inclusion in t=
he official dictionary, where they will stay for decades or centuries to co=
me? What will our grandchildren think twenty years from now when they are p=
erusing a dictionary=E2=80=99s digital pages and come across words we added=
 this year? Metaverse, booster dose, side hustle, altcoin, pumpkin spice, u=
se case, and greenwash made the list. Those words and phrases likely have s=
taying power. But sus, yeet, and adorkable=E2=80=94all new slang words in t=
his year=E2=80=99s Merriam-Webster=E2=80=99s dictionary=E2=80=94will we sti=
ll be using those in twenty years? If so, the English language will be jank=
y and in need of MacGyver[ing]=E2=80=94two other words on this year=E2=80=
=99s list.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t love this as a description of=
=C2=A0lexicography,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but the point I want to make here is that at least one SEC commis=
sioner thinks that the concept of =E2=80=9Caltcoins=E2=80=9D has staying po=
wer, and that in 20 years we=E2=80=99ll still be talking about altcoins.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0I guess that is bullish for crypto, though I am not sure. (Does t=
he permanent concept of =E2=80=9Caltcoin=E2=80=9D imply that no other crypt=
ocurrency will ever surpass Bitcoin? Isn=E2=80=99t that bearish?)=C2=A0Also=
 Peirce is generally the most crypto-sympathetic SEC commissioner. I am pre=
tty sure that SEC Chair=C2=A0Gary Gensler thinks that altcoins are sus, and=
 would prefer to yeet them into the sun.</p>
